def VarImp_top(model_name):
    
    import numpy as np
    from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve,auc
    from sklearn.metrics import average_precision_score
    from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    # plot the variable importance
    plt.rcdefaults()
    variables = model_name._model_json['output']['variable_importances']['variable'][0:10]
    y_pos = np.arange(len(variables))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (6,len(variables)/2))
    scaled_importance = model_name._model_json['output']['variable_importances']['scaled_importance'][0:10]
    ax.barh(y_pos,scaled_importance,align='center',color='green')
    ax.set_yticks(y_pos)
    ax.set_yticklabels(variables)
    ax.invert_yaxis()
    ax.set_xlabel('Scaled Importance')
    ax.set_title('Variable Importance')
    plt.show()
    
VarImp_top(rf_v1)

X_train['MB005_D'] = pd.cut(X_train['MB005'], bins = [-1,3,4,6,9,99], duplicates = 'drop').cat.add_categories('NoData')

# Encode categorical variables 
categorical_columns = ['MB007', 'MB005_D']

for column in categorical_columns:
    tempdf = pd.get_dummies(X_train[column], prefix=column)
    X_train = pd.merge(left=X_train,right=tempdf,left_index=True,right_index=True)
    X_train = X_train.drop(columns=column)

for column in categorical_columns:
    tempdf = pd.get_dummies(X_test[column], prefix=column)
    X_test = pd.merge(left=X_test,right=tempdf,left_index=True,right_index=True)
    X_test = X_test.drop(columns=column)

#!pip install shap
import shap



     























The summary plot - Global Interpretability¶
The SHAP value plot show the positive and negative relationships of the predictors with the target variable. Each dot has three characteristics. The graph below plots the SHAP values of every feature for every sample. It shorts features by the total of absolute SHAP values over all samples. The color represents the feature value (red high, blue low).


    

  • The vertical location shows the feature importance.
    • 

  • The horizontal location shows whether the effect of that value caused a higher or lower prediction.
    • 

  • Color shows whether that feature was high or low for that observation
    • 




















In [13]:



     


shap_values = shap.TreeExplainer(model).shap_values(X_train)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train)



     






















    
    































In [14]:



     


def ABS_SHAP_top(df_shap,df):
    #import matplotlib as plt
    # Make a copy of the input data
    shap_v = pd.DataFrame(df_shap)
    feature_list = df.columns
    shap_v.columns = feature_list
    df_v = df.copy().reset_index().drop('index',axis=1)
    
    # Determine the correlation in order to plot with different colors
    corr_list = list()
    for i in feature_list:
        b = np.corrcoef(shap_v[i],df_v[i])[1][0]
        corr_list.append(b)
    corr_df = pd.concat([pd.Series(feature_list),pd.Series(corr_list)],axis=1).fillna(0)
    # Make a data frame. Column 1 is the feature, and Column 2 is the correlation coefficient
    corr_df.columns  = ['Variable','Corr']
    corr_df['Sign'] = np.where(corr_df['Corr']>0,'red','blue')
    
    # Plot it
    shap_abs = np.abs(shap_v)
    k=pd.DataFrame(shap_abs.mean()).reset_index()
    k.columns = ['Variable','SHAP_abs']
    k2 = k.merge(corr_df,left_on = 'Variable',right_on='Variable',how='inner')
    k2 = k2.sort_values(by='SHAP_abs',ascending = True).iloc[-10:,:]
    colorlist = k2['Sign']
    ax = k2.plot.barh(x='Variable',y='SHAP_abs',color = colorlist, figsize=(6,4),legend=False)
    ax.set_xlabel("SHAP Value (Red = Positive Impact)")
    
ABS_SHAP_top(shap_values,X_train)

The dependence plot - Global Interpretability¶
A partial dependence plot shows the marginal effect of one or two features on the predicted outcome of a machine learning model. It tells whether the relationship between the target and a feature is linear, monotonic or more complex. It also tells interaction between features.



















In [15]:



     


shap.dependence_plot('AP003', shap_values, X_train)



     






















    
    



































Interpretation:¶
The above plot shows there might be a linear and negative trend between “AP003” and the target variable, and “AP003” interacts with “TD013” frequently. Also we can interpret that, when AP003 is 1, the impact is positive. Other than that, the impact is more negative.

The above plot shows that when MB005 is in the category of (0-3), the impact is positive to the target variable, and when MB005 is not in the category of (0-3), the impact is negative to the target variable. “MB005D(-1, 3]” also interacts with “AP003” frequently and the interaction with "AP003" is inverted between 1 or 0.

In [22]:



     


def shap_plot(j):
    explainerModel = shap.TreeExplainer(model)
    shap_values_Model = explainerModel.shap_values(S)
    p = shap.force_plot(explainerModel.expected_value, shap_values_Model[j], S.iloc[[j]])
    return(p)



     























Break the shap_plot in great details:¶
    

  • Output value: is the prediction for that observation
    • 

  • Base value: The original paper explains that the base value E(y_hat) is "the value that would be predicted if we did not know any features for the current output." In other words, it is the mean prediction, or mean(yhat). So the mean prediction of Y_test is 5.62.
    • 

  • Features: The above explanation shows features that contributes to push the final prediction away from the base value.
    • 

  • Red/blue: Those features that push the prediction higher (to the right) are shown in red, and those pushing the prediction lower are in blue. 
    •

Summary¶
The main objective of the assignment is to learn and explain the model using SHAP value.


    

  • Pick top 10 variables from H20 Random Forest Model. Prepare the data (using variable transformation, get dummies) to fit the data with SKlearn Random Forest Model. 
    • 

  • Then calculate SHAP values and interpret the model with SHAP value and relevent graphs. Each feature has a shap value contributing to the prediction. The shap value of a feature can be positive or negative.
    • 

  • Summary plot shows global interpretability. For the top three variables: AP003 shows a negative relationship with the target variable, TD013 shows a positive relationship with the target variable, and CR015 shows a negative relationship with the target variable. 
    • 

  • Dependency plot shows the marginal effect of one or two features on the predicted outcome of a machine learning model, also global interpretability. 
    • 

  • Force plot shows local interpretability for each inidividual data observation. If a feature is positively correlated to the target, a value higher than its own average will contribute positively to the prediction. If a feature is negatively correlated to the target, a value higher than its own average will contribute negatively to the prediction.
    •
